triple.typedLiteral: A botanical painting in natural pigments and ochres on eucalyptus stringy bark, depicting the native plant species 'Wanydjarrpu'. The painting features a crosshatch design in white, ochre yellow and red with a yellow border. There are two predominant tuber like forms painted in white. On the reverse of the bark, the number '4724 U' is handwritten in black ink, and there is a 'BUKU-LARRNGAY MULKA' adhesive label attached, including the artist's name and other details.

The collection consists of nine larrakitj, or painted hollow logs, and 113 bark paintings painted between 2011 and 2014 by Mulkun Wirrpanda, a senior female Yolngu artist at Yirrkala in north east Arnhem Land. These works are a product of Wirrpanda's interest in documenting the ecology of her country following her participation in a joint project with non-Indigeous artists, printmakers and academics, charting the country and yam supply at Blue Mud Bay.
The works in this collection provide a unique visual record of Yolngu knowledge of plants and food-bearing and medicinal species. Wirrpanda depicts aspects of the plants' life cycle across numerous works, including the gestational period through to fruiting and the interconnections between the food source and the extensive freshwater flood plains and rivers, beaches, sandhills, salt flats and estuaries in her Yolngu country.

A botanical painting in natural pigments and ochres on eucalyptus stringy bark, depicting the native plant species 'WANYDJARRPU'. The painting features three plant forms, one at the bottom and two at the top, in yellow-ochre and white detailing. The stems of each plant are crosshatched while the leaves are outlined in white. The background is crosshatched in white, red-brown and yellow-ochre. The painting is bordered with a thick yellow-ochre line followed by crosshatching in white, red-brown and yellow-ochre then lines of white and yellow-ochre. On the reverse of the bark, the number '4724V' is handwritten in black ink, and there is a 'BUKU-LARRNGAY MULKA' adhesive label attached, including the artist's name and other details.

Wanydjarrpu (Yolngu name) Austrodolichos errabundus (Scott) Verdc. (Latin name) Austrodolichos (Common name) This plant belongs to the Dhuwa moiety
Botanical information about this plant: Commonly found from the western side of Cape York to western Arnhem Land on well drained soils in Eucalypt savanna.

A botanical painting in natural pigments and ochres on eucalyptus stringy bark, depicting the native plant species Wandydjarrpu. The painting features three plant forms with ovoid tubers at the bottom extending into leaves at the top. The tubers are crosshatched in white, red-brown, yellow-ochre and black, and outlined in white. The leaves are white. The background is crosshatched in black, white and yellow-ochre. The entire painting is bordered in red-brown. On the reverse of the bark, the number '4609I' is handwritten in black ink on the label, and there is a 'BUKU-LARRNGAY MULKA' adhesive label attached, including the artist's name and other details.

A botanical painting in natural pigments and ochres on eucalyptus stringy bark, depicting the native plant species Wanydjarrpu. The painting features three tuber like shapes at the bottom of the bark with branch-like white lines coming out the top of each tuber. The tubers are coloured with white, black, red and yellow crosshatch designs. The background is black, white and red crosshatching. On the reverse of the bark there is a 'BUKU-LARRNGAY MULKA' adhesive label attached, including the the number '4609H' and other details.

A botanical painting in natural pigments and ochres on eucalyptus stringy bark, depicting the native plant species Wanydjarrpu. The painting features nine white plant forms arranged in three rows, each with tubers at the base and leaves protruding from the top. The tubers and background are crosshatched in red-brown, yellow ochre, white and black. On the reverse of the bark, the number '4609T' is handwritten in black ink, and there is a 'BUKU-LARRNGAY MULKA' adhesive label attached, including the artist's name and other details.

A botanical painting in natural pigments and ochres on eucalyptus stringy bark, depicting the native plant species Wanydjarrpu. The painting is split into two sections. The top section features four tuber like shapes with plants growing from them. The lower two thirds of the painting features several more tuber like shapes with leaves. The tubers and the background both feature crosshatching in ochre yellow, white, red/brown and grey. On the reverse of the bark, the number '4568S' is handwritten in black ink,and there is a 'BUKU-LARRNGAY MULKA' adhesive label attached, including the artist's name and other details.
